Here's a basic implementation of a "first loop setter" in JavaScript to calculate tempo for live looping. This example uses the browser's built-in functionalities and assumes the user indicates the start and end of a loop through button clicks.

### Basic First Loop Setter Code

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>First Loop Setter</title>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="start">Start Loop</button>
    <button id="end" disabled>End Loop</button>
    <div id="tempo">Tempo: N/A</div>

    <script>
        let startTime, endTime;

        document.getElementById('start').addEventListener('click', () => {
            startTime = Date.now();
            document.getElementById('end').disabled = false;
        });

        document.getElementById('end').addEventListener('click', () => {
            endTime = Date.now();
            const timeDiffInSeconds = (endTime - startTime) / 1000;
            const numberOfBars = 1; // For simplicity
            const beatsPerBar = 4; // Assuming 4/4 time signature
            const tempo = Math.round(numberOfBars / timeDiffInSeconds * beatsPerBar * 60);

            document.getElementById('tempo').innerText = `Tempo: ${tempo} BPM`;
            document.getElementById('end').disabled = true; // Reset
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Creative Examples of Live Looping Code

1. **Layering Loops**: Record the first loop and allow users to layer additional sounds interactively.

```javascript
const audioContext = new (window.AudioContext || window.webkitAudioContext)();
let recorder;
let audioChunks = [];

navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio: true })
    .then(stream => {
        recorder = new MediaRecorder(stream);
        recorder.ondataavailable = event => audioChunks.push(event.data);
    });

function startRecording() {
    audioChunks = [];
    recorder.start();
}

function stopRecording() {
    recorder.stop();
    recorder.onstop = () => {
        const audioBlob = new Blob(audioChunks);
        const audioUrl = URL.createObjectURL(audioBlob);
        playSound(audioUrl);
    };
}

function playSound(url) {
    const audio = new Audio(url);
    audio.play();
}
```

2. **Loop Timing Adjustments**: Automatically sync the next recording to the established tempo.

